<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[816,1475,1388,2052]" lastBlockId="21.[113,772,235,739]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
Prendini &amp; Loria (2020: 442) formally synonymized 
<taxonomicName authority="KovarIk, 2012" authorityName="KovarIk" authorityYear="2012" box="[816,1176,1420,1446]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lowei">
<emphasis box="[816,993,1420,1444]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Pandinus lowei</emphasis>
KovařÍk, 2012
</taxonomicName>
under 
<taxonomicName authority="Pocock, 1890" authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1890" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viatoris">
<emphasis box="[1274,1474,1420,1444]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Pandinus viatoris</emphasis>
Pocock, 1890
</taxonomicName>
(both now in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rossi" authorityYear="2015" box="[1252,1387,1452,1476]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandipalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1252,1387,1452,1476]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Pandipalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), citing only “ 
<emphasis box="[887,1076,1484,1508]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">unpublished data</emphasis>
” and not providing specific details or analyses to support their taxonomic act. They wrote: “ 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">
It is also evident, based firstly on the absence of consistent morphological differences, and secondly on low genetic divergence between samples collected at the 
<typeStatus box="[1310,1354,1612,1635]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">type</typeStatus>
locality of
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Kovarik, 2012" authorityName="KovarIk" authorityYear="2012" box="[816,1145,1644,1668]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lowei">
Pandinus lowei 
<emphasis box="[989,1145,1644,1668]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Kovařík, 2012</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1145,1474,1644,1668]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">, and across the distribution of</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1890" box="[816,922,1676,1700]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viatoris">P. viatoris</taxonomicName>
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">(unpublished data), that these taxa are conspecific, justifying the following synonymy</emphasis>
”. However, the claim of “ 
<emphasis box="[828,1428,1740,1764]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">the absence of consistent morphological differences</emphasis>
” is inconsistent with our data. For example, as illustrated in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 77–81" captionStartId="19.[115,192,970,992]" captionTargetBox="[113,1468,225,955]" captionTargetId="figure-563@19.[113,1474,222,955]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figures 77–81: Pedipalp chela dorsal views. Figures 77–78. Pandipalpus lowei, male (77) and female (78) paratypes from type locality. Figures 79–81. Pandipalpus viatoris, male (79) and female (80) from Democratic Republic of Congo, Kamonga (FKCP), and male (81) from Tanzania, Iringa Province (FKCP)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648864" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648864/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Figs. 77–81</figureCitation>
, there are pronounced differences in the morphometrics and granulation of the pedipalp chelae of these two species. The 
<taxonomicName box="[868,988,1868,1891]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viatorus">
<emphasis box="[868,884,1868,1891]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[901,988,1868,1891]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">viatorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male from Kamonga, 
<collectingCountry name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Democratic Republic of Congo</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[932,1012,1900,1924]" captionStart="Figures 77–81" captionStartId="19.[115,192,970,992]" captionTargetBox="[113,1468,225,955]" captionTargetId="figure-563@19.[113,1474,222,955]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figures 77–81: Pedipalp chela dorsal views. Figures 77–78. Pandipalpus lowei, male (77) and female (78) paratypes from type locality. Figures 79–81. Pandipalpus viatoris, male (79) and female (80) from Democratic Republic of Congo, Kamonga (FKCP), and male (81) from Tanzania, Iringa Province (FKCP)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648864" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648864/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
), a locality relatively close (
<quantity box="[1315,1399,1899,1924]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" unit="km" value="250.0">250 km</quantity>
) to the 
<typeStatus box="[816,862,1932,1956]" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KovarIk" authorityYear="2012" box="[986,1075,1932,1956]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lowei">
<emphasis box="[986,1002,1932,1955]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1017,1075,1932,1956]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">lowei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lusinga, Parc National de Upemba, 
<collectingCountry box="[816,1156,1964,1988]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Democratic Republic of Congo</collectingCountry>
) has distinctly more elongate pedipalp fingers and weaker manus granulation vs. the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KovarIk" authorityYear="2012" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lowei">
<emphasis box="[1451,1467,1996,2019]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[816,874,2028,2052]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">lowei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male (
<figureCitation box="[953,1035,2028,2052]" captionStart="Figures 77–81" captionStartId="19.[115,192,970,992]" captionTargetBox="[113,1468,225,955]" captionTargetId="figure-563@19.[113,1474,222,955]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figures 77–81: Pedipalp chela dorsal views. Figures 77–78. Pandipalpus lowei, male (77) and female (78) paratypes from type locality. Figures 79–81. Pandipalpus viatoris, male (79) and female (80) from Democratic Republic of Congo, Kamonga (FKCP), and male (81) from Tanzania, Iringa Province (FKCP)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648864" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648864/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">Fig. 77</figureCitation>
). The chela of another 
<taxonomicName box="[1293,1412,2028,2051]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="19" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viatorus">
<emphasis box="[1293,1309,2028,2051]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1325,1412,2028,2051]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="18">viatorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male (
<figureCitation box="[121,202,235,259]" captionStart="Figures 77–81" captionStartId="19.[115,192,970,992]" captionTargetBox="[113,1468,225,955]" captionTargetId="figure-563@19.[113,1474,222,955]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figures 77–81: Pedipalp chela dorsal views. Figures 77–78. Pandipalpus lowei, male (77) and female (78) paratypes from type locality. Figures 79–81. Pandipalpus viatoris, male (79) and female (80) from Democratic Republic of Congo, Kamonga (FKCP), and male (81) from Tanzania, Iringa Province (FKCP)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4648864" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4648864/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
) is very similar, although it originates from 
<collectingRegion box="[701,767,235,259]" country="Tanzania" name="Iringa" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Iringa</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[113,212,267,291]" name="Tanzania" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, a locality separated from Kamonga by 
<quantity box="[660,767,267,291]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="21" pageNumber="20" unit="km" value="1.1">1,100 km</quantity>
. Also very similar is the chela of another male from 
<quantity box="[700,771,299,323]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.2" pageId="21" pageNumber="20" unit="km" value="92.0">92 km</quantity>
NW of Mpika, 
<collectingCountry box="[280,361,331,355]" name="Zambia" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Zambia</collectingCountry>
(
<quantity box="[377,461,331,355]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="21" pageNumber="20" unit="km" value="460.0">460 km</quantity>
from Kamonga) (see fig. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.652" pageId="21" pageNumber="20" unit="in" value="38.0">38 in</quantity>
KovařÍk, 2012: 12). This indicates that the morphology is stable over the wide geographic range of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1890" box="[551,661,395,418]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="21" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viatoris">
<emphasis box="[551,567,395,418]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[580,661,395,418]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">viatoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(KovařÍk, 2012: 19, fig. 64), and there is no obvious character gradient that links or overlaps with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="KovarIk" authorityYear="2012" box="[387,473,459,483]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="21" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lowei">
<emphasis box="[387,403,459,482]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[415,473,459,483]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">lowei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Other diagnostic characters separating the two species were cited in KovařÍk (2012). The second justification of synonymy by “ 
<emphasis box="[516,759,523,547]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">low genetic divergence</emphasis>
“ was not demonstrated in Prendini &amp; Loria (2020), and there was no indication that the authors analyzed the 
<typeStatus box="[623,679,587,611]" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">types</typeStatus>
of these species. Considering the absence of convincing evidence for synonymy, and the documented morphological differences, we reinstate 
<taxonomicName authority="(KovarIk, 2012)" baseAuthorityName="KovarIk" baseAuthorityYear="2012" box="[258,649,683,709]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandipalpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="21" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lowei">
<emphasis box="[258,462,683,707]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">Pandipalpus lowei</emphasis>
(KovařÍk, 2012)
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species distinct from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Pocock, 1890)" baseAuthorityName="Pocock" baseAuthorityYear="1890" box="[341,621,715,739]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Pandinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="21" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viatoris">
<emphasis box="[341,448,715,738]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="20">P. viatoris</emphasis>
(Pocock, 1890)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
